TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Optimal Degree of Discretion in Monetary Policy
AU  - Athey, Susan
AU  - Atkeson, Andrew
AU  - Kehoe, Patrick J.
Y1  - 2005/09/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2005.00626.x
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1431
EP  - 1475
VL  - 73
IS  - 5
KW  - Rules vs. discretion
KW  - time inconsistency
KW  - optimal monetary policy
KW  - inflation targets
KW  - inflation caps
KW  - activist monetary policy
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2005.00626.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - How much discretion should the monetary authority have in setting its policy? This question is analyzed in an economy with an agreed-upon social welfare function that depends on the economy's randomly fluctuating state. The monetary authority has private information about that state. Well designed rules trade off society's desire to give the monetary authority discretion to react to its private information against society's need to prevent that authority from giving in to the temptation to stimulate the economy with unexpected inflation, the time inconsistency problem. Although this dynamic mechanism design problem seems complex, its solution is simple: legislate an inflation cap. The optimal degree of monetary policy discretion turns out to shrink as the severity of the time inconsistency problem increases relative to the importance of private information. In an economy with a severe time inconsistency problem and unimportant private information, the optimal degree of discretion is none.
ER  - 

